Neutron TOF facility GELINA.
Transmission measurements at the 25-m station have been
performed with the accelerator operating at 50, 400 and
800 Hz. At capture measurement -at 50 Hz and 400 Hz.
M.M.
Entry was sent 30.07.2013 to author P.Schillebeeckx to
approve.
Resonance shape analysis RSA.
Capture:
Normalization accounts for energy independent factors-
the absolute neutron flux, the efficiency of the flux
detector and the solid angle subtended by the target
and the C6D6 detectors. The normalization constant was
considered as a free parameter in the RSA and was
defined by resonances for which the parameters were
determined from the transmission data.
Resonance parameters were extracted by a simultaneous
least squares adjustment of the capture and
transmission data using REFIT, taking into account
the Doppler broadening, self-shielding and scattering
in the sample, the attenuation of gamma-rays in sample,
the response of the TOF-spectrometer and the neutron
sensitivity of the capture detection system, also
the target characteristics - inhomogeneities, isotopic
composition and impurities.
The flight path length of the 50 m transmission station
at GELINA (determined from the transmission dip of the
6.673+-0.001 eV resonance in 238U+n) was used as a
reference to determine the resonance energies.
Resonance parameters files are the result of a combined
analysis of available experimental data together with a
RSA of transmission and capture data on nat-Cd at
GELINA.
For backgrounds in transmission:
-contribution due to the 2.2 MeV gamma-ray resulting
from neutron capture in hydrogen dominates the
background for t < 100 micros at 25 m and 50 m flight
path lengths.
-due to neutrons scattered inside the detector station
and due to neutrons scattered at other flight paths.
The background level was continuously monitored by
performing all measurements with at least one fixed
black resonance filter in the beam.
For dead-time effects- for neutron energies below
500 eV was < 2% in transmission.
Capture:
- for gamma-ray attenuation in sample, in-exit window,
in air;
- maximum correction for the dead time was < 1% in flux
measurement (dead time was 3500 ns); the dead time for
the capture measurement systems was 2800 ns; for the
measurements at 12.5 m and 30 m the maximum dead time
corrections were less than 20% and 5%, respectively.
Bias effects due to such dead time corrections are
- for backgrounds :
- time independent component due to ambient radiation
and possible radioactivity in the sample and its
surroundings; estimated from measurements when the
accelerator was switched off;
- time dependent component independent of the sample;
deduced from measurements without a sample in the beam;
- time dependent component depending on the sample
characteristics - due to  neutrons and gamma-rays
scattered from the sample; smooth part of this
time-dependent background component (mainly due to
potential scattering in the sample) was determined from
measurements with a 0.5-mm thick 208Pb sample.
BaF3 proportional counters are used to monitor
the stability of the accelerator and to normalize
TOF-spectra to the same total neutron intensity.
Transmission:
6.35-mm thick, 101.6-mm diameter NE912 Li-glass
scintillator enriched to 95% in 6Li, coupled to a
boron-free quartz windowed EMI9823-QKB photomultiplier
The detector was placed at a distance of 49.34 m from
the exit face of the moderator.
Used to detect neutrons - at 50 m path.
NE905 Li-glass scintillator, enriched to 95% in 6Li,
110.0 mm diameter and 12.7 mm thick, placed in a
thin-walled Al can, viewed by two EMI9823-QKB PMTs.
Used to detect neutrons - at 25 m path.
Capture:
Gamma-rays were detected by a pair of C6D6
detectors, each positioned at an angle of 125deg with
respect to the direction of the neutron beam,
coupled to a boron-free quartz windowed PMT.
The linearity and resolution of the C6D6 detectors were
monitored on a weekly basis by measurements of the
2.6 MeV gamma-ray from the 232Th decay chain.
The energy dependent neutron spectrum below
150 keV was measured in parallel with a 10B Frisch
gridded ionization chamber placed at about 80 cm before
the sample. Cathode loaded with two back-to-back
layers of B-10 with an effective diameter of 84 mm
and areal density of about 40 microg/cm2, evaporated on
30-microm thick Al backing; the entrance and exit
windows had a thickness of 40 microm. The chambers were
operated with a continuous flow of a mixture of Ar(90%)
and methane (10%) at atmospheric pressure.
Uncertainty of normalization.
Neutron TOF facility GELINA.
Transmission measurements at the 25-m station have been
performed with the accelerator operating at 50, 400 and
800 Hz. At capture measurement -at 50 Hz and 400 Hz.
Moderated neutron beam.
Transmission:
B-10 overlap filter, areal density 0.008 at/b, was used
to eliminate neutrons from previous burst. Li-carbonate
+ resin, Pb and Cu-collimators were used to reduce the
neutron beam to a diameter of 35 mm at the sample
position. 15-mm diameter neutron beam at the sample
position. A 5-mm thick Pb filter was placed in front of
the sample changer to reduce the intense gamma-ray
flash.
Capture:
Moderated neutron beam was collimated to about 75 mm
diameter at the sample position by Li-carbonate, Cu-
and Pb-collimators.
Discrimination level of the capture detection systems
at 12.5 m and 30 m corresponded to 200 keV and 150 keV
deposited energy. The total energy detection principle
in combination with the pulse height weighting
technique (PHWT) was applied to arrive at a detection
efficiency for a capture event directly proportional
to the total gamma-ray energy liberated in the capture
event. Weighting functions were calculated by Monte
Carlo simulations and validated by experiment ( see
REL-REF of A.Borella+).
